Dialogue:
Who is it?
Yes?
I don’t know what you’re talking about.
I’d like to see your warrant.
What girl?
A doll was stolen out of my van if that’s what you mean. I was giving it to my niece for her first communion.
I don’t have to talk to you. I know my rights.
What are you doing? Are you arresting me?
Fine, let’s go downtown, my lawyer will get me out.
Then maybe I will go visit my little niece.
Let me go!
Ow!
Go to hell.
I don't know!
Oh my God, I am heartly sorry for having offended Thee --
Police brutality! Torture!

See, I knew it. I’m cursed. First the radio, then the weather, now
this...terrible accident.
Doing his rounds. Security check. Slipped off deck, I guess.
What are you thinking?
Why?
Now?
By accident. And I appreciate your position. But you need to
appreciate mine. I’m three hours off schedule...
I get it. You’re investigating a crime. But from my perspective...
We’re all just trying to make a living here. Can’t we handle this
after we’ve finished our run...?
I’m telling you as captain of this ship there is absolutely nothing
illegal or...or...suspicious...
Yeah. Just need to sit--
Where am I?
And my ship?
I should be there.
Had a package of chew in my shirt pocket, any chance it’s around?
Time I quit anyway. Bad habit.
Trip like this. Your eyes always scan the horizon for pirates.
Never expected them to be part of my own crew.
They called me a hero last time
this happened. Because I got my
crew off the boat.
Truth is, I told my crew to run to
the lifeboats. I ran too, not fast
enough...
I knew exactly who he was... I was too scared to do anything.
Just lucky, I guess...
Had to stop him. Hijackers locked the crew up in the mess. But
Vilandro needed me to work the comm. It was him and me...
I wasn’t giving up my ship. Not to
Vilandro, not again... Radio got
destroyed in the fight... I tossed
Vilandro overboard. Hoped someone
would find the body.
Good would be me back on my ship.
That’s my brand...
Don’t know what you’re--
He wasn’t my friend.
That bastard tortured me for ten days, made me beg for my life...
Humiliated me... and somehow believed I was going into business with him...
I just needed him to set up the hijacking.
He figured out that I’d taken the money off the container before weeven left port. He was angry.

Are you familiar with Godwin's Law?
It's the idea that the endpoint of any intellectual debate is one side
calling the other Nazis. I'm not a Nazi.
I prefer Americanist.
I don't believe in violence as a means to any social end.
Looking at public policies through a single, objective lens: is it good for our country?
I told your colleagues last year: I don't know about the bomb. But I do
know New York has more synagogues than any city outside Israel.
It pushed out a hospice. And we don't have enough of those.
I'm passionate about our country not going bankrupt. But very soon, 1 out
of every 3 dollars we spend will go to medical costs.
It's not a joke. We throw away billions on people in their last
year of life -- seventy-five percent of it in their final few months. Do
you not see the absurdity of that?
We should be putting them in hospices, letting them die the way God intended,
and using that money --
You work for the United States government. Don't you care what happens to it?
Or you, Agent Casillas?
Stop taking notes, and engage. Tell me you're worried about the impact
on your community.
Let me explain to you why we have to make economic decisions rather than
emotional ones.
Or do you -- and your partner -- feel like you may be on shaky ground?
Don't you have anything to say?
Am I dismayed by the bombings? Yes. Am I surprised by them? No...
The violence in that community -- like the drugs and unemployment --
are symptoms of an underlying dysfunction no one wants to address.
We can only help these people if we're honest about root causes.
Families where the father's in prison, the mother can't do it all by herself --
What exactly are you accusing me of?
Conspiracy. Which means you have no proof that I actually did anything.
I'd like to call my lawyer. My phone's in my bag. Can I reach in
and get it without you shooting me?
Now, I'm just getting the number.

I’m sorry -- ?
It was an old ring box. Lisa’s grandmother gave it to her. Why?
For the last time: I loved my wife. I didn’t hurt her. And until this
morning, I had no idea there wasany “safe room” in my house.
For the last time: I loved my wife. I didn’t hurt her. And until this
morning, I had no idea there was any “safe room” in my house.
The house was gutted before Lisa and I moved in two years ago. She
oversaw all of the construction, I just signed the checks.The house was gutted before Lisa 
and I moved in two years ago. 
She oversaw all of the construction, I
just signed the checks.
We had a few arguments about money back then. She said she wanted
one, but we were so over budget
that I put my foot down. Obviously, she didn’t listen. 
I showered before I left... there was traffic...
...like to thank the police again for finding the man who killed my
wife. I would have liked to have seen him stand trial for what he
did, but I take some comfort in the fact he can’t hurt anyone else...
Excuse me?
You’re Mr. Holmes, right? We met the other day --
I never even heard the name “Peter Saldua” until the police told me he
was the man who’d killed Lisa --
So... according to you... I tricked a stalker into hunting my wife.
I’m sorry, but that just doesn’t make any sense to me. Stalkers
stalk. Eventually, he would’ve seen us together and realized I was up to something.
Hypothetically, Mr. Holmes, a man
wants out of his marriage to his
very wealthy wife. He knows that,
over the course of their
relationship, he’s signed a
prenuptial agreement that says he
gets nothing if he leaves her...
and a living trust that says he
gets everything if she dies.
Hypothetically... wouldn’t that man
be smarter to look for a way to
trigger the clauses in the second
document as opposed to the first?
As to the lengths such a man --
hypothetically, a very intelligent
and careful man -- would go to keep
his hands clean, well... how better
to commit a murder than manipulate
someone else into doing it for you?
Not at all. I can’t promise it’ll
change my mind about suing the
department for what your
“consultant” did to my car... but
it’s a start.
You have a funny way of saying
you’re sorry, Captain.
No. I did not treat Peter Saldua.
I never even met the man. Now. If
that’s all, I’m late for an
appointment with my attorney --
You know you’re just digging
yourself deeper, right? Putting
this man in the same room with me --
This is ridiculous --
Okay, Mr. Holmes. Amaze me. What
do a bag of rice and an overturned
washing machine have to do with
anything?
It’s okay, Peter. It’s okay. I’m
here for you. Let’s try upping
your meds, see where that leads us.

Need any help at the office?
Market’s looking pretty bullish at the moment.
Good of you to make an effort.
I can lend you a tie if you want. Got a lovely burgundy one. Silk. Hand crafted.
Terrance. This is my sister Anna. And my brother Joseph.
My father was a great man. It's disrespectful to leave him lying out like this.
He passed me by moments later.
Be careful. It’s rather expensive.
Yes. Don't do that.
Dad always liked to take a walk before lunch. Clear his head from business. I do it myself sometimes.
It’s a business thing. Take the client out to play golf or go shooting. Dad liked to keep his aim in.
Everything he did was legal-
I heard it too, in the library. Was doing some reading- Harvard Review of Business.
It’s a shotgun. It’s kept mounted in the hallway.
Can’t have you running around, firing off guns willy nilly.
You sure it's not the murder weapon?
Well, you seem to know your stuff. If there's anything else you need-
Am I now in charge of the company? Uh- I suppose technically- yes. Yes I am.
They’ll be devastated. He was well loved by everyone he worked with.
I’m the only one who’s qualified to do it.
Joseph. Are you serious? The only time he’s got involved with the company is across the bloody picket line.
Joseph protested some of Dad’s resort plans. Dad almost had him thrown in jail.
Um... you know, I don’t. Emily will though.
No. I think maybe that-
Yes. She keeps track of these things. I didn’t spend much time in Dad’s study-
...Dad’s study... I guess it’s my study now. I always expected him to hand the keys over to me. Father to son. Never imagined it would be like this.
Have a seat.
You know one day all this will be mine. I'm very... important.
You could be important too. Come on.
I'm sorry- I didn't mean to- Rosie- please-
- don't tell dad...
I was drunk. It was a mistake. Stupid, foolish mistake and... I’ve paid for it.
...he stopped my wages. My expense account. It was under review. Dad said if I made another mistake he’d bump me right down to the same level as the doorman.
It was. He didn’t even tell me face to face. Just sent me a memo. That’s his way.
I doubt it.
Sometimes I think they just don’t realise how hurtful they can be. I’m used to his temper, his anger- but it’s the way he was so dismissive of me-
...What? No, no... I couldn't do that... he was my father...
No- I've always- always been loyal to my father. No matter what- we had a strong relationship. I mean it wasn't like him and Joseph. We didn't have thos kinds of problems, you know?
Well, you’d think so. I did. But maybe I was wrong. Last night... I heard them arguing...
I don’t know. Ever since dad’s body was found, I’ve thought about it and turned it over in my head and...
I'm loyal to my family. Above all.
And... I just hope, with all my heart, that Joseph feels the same way.
Might be morning before the power comes back on. We've got some more of these camping lights stored away for emergencies.
And he throws coins out the window and works out the guy was pushed.
It's pretty old.
Um... yes. That's right.
No- your officer, he said it had to be the pistol-
This is ridiculous-
Wait, sorry... you actually think it was me?
What possible reason would I have for killing my father?
You can't be serious-
I'm calling my lawyer. This is nothing short of harassment.
Don't you dare say that!
...He was going to cut us out. All of us! We'd have nothing!

Yeah. Hey Mitch! Why aren’t these pallets on the truck?
Last time I saw her? About a month ago at Dad’s.
Not really. Honestly, we didn’t have much in common, aside from our last name. She always wanted to see the best in everyone...
That’s right. Like that guy who killed her. She did everything to help him. Even brought him here and begged me to give him a job.
This is a business, not a charity. My employees mess up, I lose my bond.
I don’t know... Maybe if I had helped him, things would be different. Maybe she’d still be alive. Or then again, maybe we’d both be dead.
She was upset. We both were.
What does that have to do with her murder?
Is this some kind of joke? You already caught the killer.
Of course.
I was traveling on business.
Check the stamps and you’ll find I was out of the country for all three murders.
Yeah, I'm a little under it.
Anyone stop in to see me today?
Stay back!
I said stay back.
Shut up.
I'll blow your head off.
Shut up!
OPEN THE GATE!
Self-righteous bitch would’ve given it all away to the ungrateful poor. She didn’t deserve it.
It’s not over. Now drop your guns or I blow his brains out.

She's worked for us three summers in a row now. Lovely girl.
Yes it is.
I can't even think about it. Try that.
And caraway.
No, there's no shame in it. A lot of butter. The great thing about food, it's necessity and indulgence all in one.
Hey, it wasn't me by the way. I have twenty staff that will tell you. I only ever leave the kitchen to take a leak or yell at customers.
Attention Randall. Pay it.
Settle down now everyone. Settle down. These are agents of the California Bureau of Investigation. They want to talk to you a moment.
Help me put this on the bed.
What?
Why are you here?
Oh no.
You wanted this too. Don't pretend you didn't.
--I swear to God woman! One more word...

It's unbelievable. And from the parking lot. I was practically right there.
No.
Shhh.
I know she took off first, but I'd need to look at her timecard to be exact.
Sad but true.
She was by no means a gifted server, betty butterfinger we called her, but she had a good spirit...
She left at eleven twenty-five.
She went out that door...
...And that's the last we saw of her.
Yes. I'll get you a full list. It's okay, Raquel. Come in.
These people are here to find out what happened to poor Melanie.
Nothing to worry about.
Can I call you a cab, ma'am?
Hey!
How?
He's lying. They'd be in here arresting us by now if they were here.
Nobody. We should just kill them and get out of here.
Oh, now he's thinking.
I told you we should wait! I told you we--

Two utensils per dish. Plates at the beginning, napkins at the end. Savoury to sweet.
Father Brown!
So glad you could come.
Couldn't resist sharing my good fortune.
Wouldn't dream of it.
Just one moment...
Too busy for scones and tea?
Come afterwards. Please. Won't be the same without you.
Wonderful.
So what do you think?
The new clock tower.
New roofing plates. Cast iron dials. Brand new bell. Kembleford will hear its first resounding bellow at 3pm. Precisely.
What do you mean?
You can’t tell that from a pocket watch. You’re pulling my leg.
Norman!
Forgive my brother.
I'm cutting you off.
Father left a clause in the inheritance. It entrusts me with the purse strings – including all real estate holdings. I’m invoking it.
You think I wanted it to come to this? You’re out of control. Drinking, gambling, indulging your basest appetites...
It's there in black and white.
It’s not too late for you, Norman. You can still be saved. Please. Let us pray.
I’ll be fine. Can’t let my brother’s shenanigans ruin the day.
Thank you everyone for coming – and my sincere apologies for the fracas earlier. We won’t let it spoil the day. We’ve been blessed with beautiful sunshine, and in about... ten seconds... we’ll be blessed with the sound of glorious bells...
Norman! No...
I'm not going anywhere.
Isn't that obvious?
The murderer. He attacked him less than an hour before – in front of dozens of witnesses.
You don’t need a confession. Look at his head. Who else could deliver such a blow?
No...
That's not possible.
Look at her – she has neither the strength nor the brutality to...
Elizabeth...
I tried so hard to save him.
I can’t believe Elizabeth could do this. It had to be Simeon.
Not of murder. Not her. It’s not in her nature.
Trust you to look for mysteries when the truth’s right in front of your eyes.
And your penchant for spy novels and crossword puzzles? They’re forced upon you, are they?
Then you admit Elizabeth may be innocent?
Then speak to the Inspector. You know him better than I do. Tell him -
When has that stopped you before? I have some snacks. I’ll put them out.
Fine.
Did you speak to Elizabeth?
And?
Why won't you admit it?
Your wife is in prison for a crime she didn't commit.
Do you not fear eternity in hell?
Stop it!
Do you even care about your wife?
See?
Have you gone mad?
What are you doing up here?
In case you haven’t noticed, I’ve had a lot on my mind.
Where did you get that?
What are you talking ab–
Are you accusing me of...?
How dare you.
You’re far too tactile, Father. Has anyone ever told you that?
The sanctity of confession? I purge myself, you let me go scot free?
You're a fool.
Yes, I took the hammer.
My only intention was to reset the clock.
I could forgive him almost anything... Avarice, lust, even murder... But not that.
And so in a burst of pure passion... the hammer flew from my hand...
It felt so good... Because I knew my hand was guided. I was but a vessel of the Lord’s will. His agent. It was what He wanted.
How could it not be so? From up here? What’s the alternative? That it was chance? Luck? There’s no such thing.
Everything has order. Everything has meaning. This was divine intervention.
Yes, my brother is dead. But it was by God’s hand, not mine. I shall not repent.
I have no such thing.
I answer to one higher power and He will judge me righteous.
No...
Thank you for your counsel, Father. I’ll be leaving now.
They'll see she's innocent.
God will save her.
You were right... I’m a wicked man.
I’ll be fine. Can’t let my brother’s shenanigans ruin the day.

Shawn. That's a nice name.
Wow.
Yeah. You know, you could probably change that. What's your mom's maiden
name?
Wow, yeah. "Teets" as in--
Hey, I was raised on a farm.
I had this most adorable little pet goat named Cassie.
Yeah. Did you ever have any, you know, pets growing up? What were their
names? Oh, what's your favorite color?
That is a very nice name.
So, navy blue is your favorite color? Mine's green.
You know, you seem European. You sure you don't have family history there?
What's your mother's maiden name?
This is absurd!

Oh, well, hello, me buckos. I'm Marvin. Welcome to Shenanigans, home of the
world-famous Blarney Stone fajitas.Ha, ha. Very funny. Please stop. My tummy's aching from
laughing so hard. Do you guys want a table or what?
That's the one.
Whatever floats your boat, man. (stamps GUS) It's for our
nighttime events there. But hey, you can have it in the daytime, too.
We have speed dating here.
Yeah. Don't laugh. It's actually one of our most popular events. Guys come in
here, sign up, they put down 100 bucks and they get fixed up with all sorts of
people on little six-minute mini-dates.
100 bucks.
How about you guys either get a table or I'm going to have to ask you to leave
the podium?
No, but I can say "police" if you don't get your butts out of here. (turns to
other customers and speaks in brogue) Hello there! I'm Marvin. Welcome to
Shenanigans. Home of the world-famous Blarney Stone fajitas.
Look, I don't know anything about any crime. I just ... I used the names and
the numbers to get dates, man, that's it.
I don't have 100 bucks to slap down on some entrance fee, not on my crap
salary, so, yeah. And besides, that's why they go there. They go there for dates,
right? So why not me?
Look, okay, come on, all right? All I did was I took some questionnaires
out of the trash. That's it. What's the charge? "Not littering"?
So if you don't have anything more, I'd like to get to work.
You got it.

Taxi for Sherlock Holmes.
Doesn’t mean you don’t need one.
You see, no one ever thinks about
the cabbie. It’s like we’re invisible. Just the back of a head. Proper advantage for a serial
killer.
Oh, yes. And I’ll tell you what
else - if you go and get the coppers now, I won’t run, I’ll sit quiet and they can take me
down. I promise.
Because you’re not going to do
that.
Am I not?
I didn’t kill those four people,
Mr. Holmes. I spoke to them, and they killed themselves. Go and get the coppers now,
and I promise you this - I will never tell you what I said.
And you won’t ever understand how
those four people died. Which result do you care about?
On Sherlock - agonised. He glances up the windows to his flat - all he has to do is call
out. But ... but ...
Let me take you for a ride.
I’m not going to kill you, Mr.
Holmes. I’m going to talk to you. And you’re going to kill yourself.
Oh, I recognised you - soon as I
saw you chasing my cab. Sherlock Holmes. I was warned about you. I’ve been on your
website too - brilliant stuff, loved it.
There’s someone out there who’s
noticed you.
You’re too modest, Mr. Holmes.
You’ve got yourself a fan!
On Sherlock. What? What?? SHERLOCK
Tell me more.
That’s all your going to know - in
this life time.But this is what you’re really
addicted to, isn’t it? This is the only fix that works. You’ll do anything, anything at
all - not to be bored.
You know exactly where we are, you
know every street in London.
It’s open, the cleaners are in. Thing about being a cabbie, you
always know a quiet spot for a murder. I’m surprised more of us don’t branch out.
It gets better, don’t worry.
Oh, I don’t. It’s much better than
What do you think? It’s up to you.
You’re the one who’s going to die here.
SHERLOCK No, I’m not.
That’s what they all say.
Shall we talk?
Call that a risk. Nah. This is a
risk.
Oh, I like this bit. Cos you don’t get it yet, do you? But you’re about to. I just have to do ... this!
Weren’t expect that, were you. Oh,
you are gonna love this.
SHERLOCK Love what?
Sherlock Holmes! Look at you.
Here in the flesh. That website of yours! Your fan told me about it.
My fan?
SHERLOCK
You are brilliant, you are - you
are a proper genius. “The Science Of Deduction”. That’s proper thinking. Now between
you and me, sitting here, why can’t people think! Doesn’t it drive you mad. Why can’t
people just think??
95.
Don’t look it, do I? Funny little
man, driving a cab. But you’ll know better in a minute. Chances are, it will be the last
thing you ever know.
There’s a good bottle and there’s a
bad bottle. Take a pill from the good bottle, you live. Take a pill from the bad bottle, you
die.
In every way.
Wouldn’t be a game if you knew.
You’re the one who chooses.
I haven’t told you the best bit
yet. Whatever bottle you choose, I take a pill from the other one.
And then together, we take our medicine.
I won’t cheat. It’s your choice.
I’ll take whichever pill you don’t.
Holmes?
This is what you did? To all of
And now I’m giving it to you. Take
a moment. Get yourself together. I want your best game.
I’ve played four times. I’m alive.
It’s not chance, Mr. Holmes. It’s chess. It’s a game of chess, with one move, and one
survivor. And this --
Did I just give you the good
bottle, or the bad bottle? You can choose either one. You’ve got to admit - as serial
killers go, I’m verging on nice.
Are you ready yet, Mr. Holmes?
Ready to play. SHERLOCK
Play what? It’s a 50-50 chance.
You’re not playing the numbers -
you’re playing me. Did I give you the good pill, or the bad pill. Is it bluff, double-bluff,
triple- bluff ...
SHERLOCK It’s still chance.
Four people, in a row. It’s not
chance.
It’s genius. I know how people
think. I know how people think I think. I can see it all like a map in my head. Everyone’s
so stupid. Even you.
Of course - maybe God just loves
me.
Time to play.
Told me what?
So are you.
Aneurism - right in here. Any
breath could be my last.
I’ve outlived four people. That’s
the most fun you can have, with an aneurism.
Oh, you are good, aren’t you? SHERLOCK But how?
When I die, they won’t get much, my
kids. Not a lot of money in driving cabs.
SHERLOCK Or serial killing.
For every life I take, money goes
to my kids. The more I kill, they better off they’ll be. You see? Nicer than you think.
Who’d be a fan of Sherlock Holmes.
On Sherlock. Getting to it now - fascinated.
You’re not the only person who
enjoys a good murder. There’s someone else out there, just like you. Except you’re just a
man. And he’s so much more.
There’s a name that no one says.
I’m not saying it either. Now. Enough chatter. It’s time to choose.
You can take a 50-50 chance, or I
can shoot you through the head. Funnily enough, no one’s ever gone for that option.
Are you sure. SHERLOCK Definitely. The gun.
Don’t want to phone a friend? SHERLOCK The gun.
None of the others.
Before you go, did you figure it
out? Which one’s the good bottle.
Which one, then? Which one would
you have taken. Just so I know if I could have beaten you.
Come on. Play the game
Oh! Interesting!
What do you think? Shall we? 
Really, what do you think? Can you
beat me? Are you clever enough? Are you really sure? Bet your life?
Well? Shall we play? For real, shall we?
You get bored, I know you do - a
man like you, so clever. But what’s the point in being clever if you can’t prove it.
But this is what you’re really
addicted to, isn’t it? This is the only fix that works. You’ll do anything, anything at

You’re not bored now, are you? And
isn’t it good?
... no ...
